Most recent game I remember not enjoying was "The Outer Worlds", by Obsidian Entertainment.
The game was overly hyped before its release, since it was being developed by people who had worked on a very good RPG game, popular for having the best story out of that game's last three installments (Fallout New Vegas).
As such, I expected good writing in "The Outer Worlds", or at least anything unique on it that could hold me in and entertain. Instead I got your average sci-fi "Rich people are always the evil cruel monsters! The rebels were actually the good guys!" story that felt too much like a clear propaganda. That combined with the fact the NPCs all had the same punchable smug face, and gameplay being "Meh" as a typical "adventure FPS".
The issue wasn't the game being political, the issue was the game was very poorly written accompanied by clearly forced choices, with a tedious repetitive gameplay, soul-less characters, and a horrible inventory management.

I felt like I was doing a chore the entire game, without any real improvements throughout it.
